\id PHM - Wycliffe’s Bible Modern Spelling, Word Files Text Conversion and standardization, A. Camus 05 2019
\h PHILEMON
\toc1 PHILEMON
\toc2 Philemon
\toc3 PHM
\mt1 PHILEMON
\c 1
\cl CHAPTER 1
\p 
\v 1 Paul, the bound of Christ Jesus, and Timothy, brother, to Philemon, beloved, and our helper,
\p 
\v 2 and to Apphia, most dear sister, and to Archippus, our even-knight, and to the church that is in thine house,
\p 
\v 3 grace \em be\em* to you, and peace of God our Father, and of the Lord Jesus Christ.
\p 
\v 4 I do thankings to my God, ever-more making mind of thee, in my prayers,
\p 
\v 5 hearing thy charity, and faith, that thou hast in the Lord Jesus, and to all holy men,
\p 
\v 6 that the communing of thy faith be made open, in knowing of all good thing in Christ Jesus.
\p 
\v 7 And I had great joy and comfort in thy charity, for the entrails of holy men rested \add [or were refreshed]\add* by thee, brother.
\p 
\v 8 For which thing I having much trust in Christ Jesus, to command to thee that that pertaineth to profit;
\p 
\v 9 but I beseech more for charity, since thou art such as the old Paul, and now the bound of Jesus Christ.
\p 
\v 10 I beseech thee for my son Onesimus, whom I in bonds begat,
\p 
\v 11 which sometime was unprofitable to thee, but now profitable, both to thee and to me;
\p 
\v 12 whom I sent again to thee. And receive thou him as mine entrails;
\p 
\v 13 whom I would withhold with me, that he should serve for thee to me in bonds of the gospel;
\p 
\v 14 but without thy counsel I would not do anything, that thy good should not be as of need, but willful.
\p 
\v 15 For peradventure therefore he departed from thee for a time, that thou shouldest receive him without end;
\p 
\v 16 now not as a servant, but for a servant a most dear brother \add [or but more than a servant, most dear brother]\add*, most to me; and how much more to thee, both in \add [the]\add* flesh and in the Lord?
\p 
\v 17 Therefore if thou hast me a fellow, receive him as me;
\p 
\v 18 for if he hath anything annoyed thee, either oweth, areckon thou this thing to me.
\p 
\v 19 I, Paul, wrote with mine hand, I shall yield; that I say not to thee, that also thou owest to me thyself.
\p 
\v 20 So, brother, I shall use thee in the Lord; \add [full]\add*-fill thou mine entrails in Christ.
\p 
\v 21 I trusting of thine obedience wrote to thee, witting that thou shalt do over that that I say.
\p 
\v 22 Also make thou ready to me an house to dwell in; for I hope that by your prayers I shall be given to you.
\p 
\v 23 Epaphras, prisoner with me in Christ Jesus, greeteth thee well,
\p 
\v 24 and Marcus, Aristarchus, Demas, Lucas, mine helpers.
\p 
\v 25 The grace of our Lord Jesus Christ \em be\em* with your spirit. Amen. 
